<Layout title="The Legal Costs of Selling a Brisbane Property: What Sellers Need to Budget | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Legal fees, disbursements, commission, and compliance certificates all reduce your net sale proceeds. Here is a full breakdown of what a Brisbane seller should budget before they list." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the legal costs of selling a property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The main legal costs of selling a Brisbane property are conveyancing fees ($1,200 to $2,500 for a standard residential sale), disbursements including title search fees, land tax clearance certificate, PEXA electronic settlement fee, and rates clearance certificate (typically $300 to $500 in total). The ATO clearance certificate is free but requires 28 days to process. The agent's commission and marketing costs are separate and are typically the largest seller costs."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does a conveyancer charge to sell a Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Brisbane conveyancer or solicitor typically charges between $1,200 and $2,500 for a standard residential sale. This fee covers preparing or reviewing the contract of sale, responding to requisitions from the buyer's solicitor, obtaining title searches and clearance certificates, and attending to settlement. Disbursements are charged on top of this fee."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the total cost of selling a $1.2 million Brisbane home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For a Brisbane home selling at $1.2 million, the approximate total cost to sell is $33,000 to $40,000 before capital gains tax. This includes agent commission at around 2.2% ($26,400), marketing and vendor-paid advertising ($5,000 to $10,000), legal fees and disbursements ($1,500 to $2,800), and building compliance certificates including pool safety and smoke alarm ($200 to $400)."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Legal Costs of Selling a Brisbane Property: What Sellers Need to Budget
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Legal fees are a direct deduction from your net sale proceeds. Understanding them before you list avoids surprises at settlement and helps you set realistic expectations for what you will actually walk away with.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane sellers have a general sense of the agent's commission before they list. Far fewer have a clear picture of the full set of costs that will be deducted from their sale proceeds at settlement. Legal fees, disbursements, compliance certificates, and the ATO clearance certificate are all real costs, and underestimating them leads to a less accurate picture of your net position. This article sets out each cost category, what it covers, and the ranges you should budget for a standard Brisbane residential sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The conveyancing fee</h2>
      <p>The core legal cost is the conveyancing fee charged by the seller's solicitor or conveyancer for managing the sale. For a standard residential transaction in Brisbane, this fee typically falls between $1,200 and $2,500. The range reflects differences in firm type, transaction complexity, and whether the property involves any complicating factors such as a tenancy, a deceased estate, a trust structure, or a body corporate.</p>

      <p>The conveyancing fee covers the core professional work involved in the sale: reviewing or preparing the contract of sale, responding to formal requisitions from the buyer's solicitor, obtaining the various clearance certificates and search results required to settle, reviewing the settlement statement, and attending to electronic settlement through the PEXA platform. If complications arise, such as a caveator who needs to be dealt with or a title issue that requires resolution, additional legal work will be charged at an hourly rate on top of the base fee.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disbursements</h2>
      <p>Disbursements are additional costs incurred during the conveyancing process and passed through to the seller. They are not the solicitor's fee for their time but rather third-party costs the solicitor pays on your behalf. The main disbursements for a Brisbane property sale are:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Title search fees:</strong> The seller's solicitor obtains a current title search from the Queensland titles registry to confirm ownership and identify any registered interests such as caveats, mortgages, or easements. This typically costs $30 to $50.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Land tax clearance certificate:</strong> A clearance certificate from the Queensland Revenue Office confirms there is no outstanding land tax liability on the property. This costs approximately $30 to $80 depending on whether expedited processing is required.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">PEXA electronic settlement fee:</strong> Most Queensland property settlements now take place through the PEXA electronic platform rather than a physical settlement. The PEXA fee for a sale transaction is approximately $115 to $140.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Rates clearance certificate:</strong> Brisbane City Council (or the relevant local council for properties outside Brisbane proper) issues a clearance confirming the current rates balance and any outstanding amounts that need to be adjusted at settlement. Fees vary by council.</p>

      <p>In total, disbursements for a standard Brisbane residential sale typically add $300 to $500 to the legal costs, on top of the conveyancing fee.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Compliance certificates</h2>
      <p>Queensland law requires sellers to provide certain compliance certificates at or before settlement. The most common are pool safety certificates and smoke alarm compliance certificates.</p>

      <p>A pool safety certificate confirms the pool fence and gate meet Queensland's pool safety standards. If the property does not have a current certificate, a licensed pool safety inspector must assess the property and issue one before settlement. Costs for pool safety inspections and any required rectification work vary but a straightforward inspection typically costs $150 to $250.</p>

      <p>Smoke alarm compliance certificates confirm the property meets Queensland's interconnected photoelectric smoke alarm requirements. For properties that already comply, this is a simple and inexpensive certificate. Properties that require upgrades to their smoke alarm installations will face higher costs. Budget $150 to $250 for a standard smoke alarm compliance inspection on a Brisbane house, excluding any rectification work.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent's commission</h2>
      <p>The agent's commission is not a legal cost, but it is the largest single cost most sellers pay at settlement and it is worth including in any honest cost-to-sell summary. In Brisbane, commission rates for residential sales typically range from 2% to 2.5% of the sale price plus GST, though this is negotiable and varies between agents and firms. At 2.2% plus GST (2.42% inclusive), on a $1.2 million sale, the commission is $29,040. On a $900,000 sale at the same rate, it is $21,780.</p>

      <p>Commission is deducted from the sale proceeds at settlement, not paid separately. Your conveyancer will show this figure on the settlement statement alongside the other deductions. It is worth confirming the exact commission rate and the GST-inclusive figure with your agent before you sign the appointment form.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing and vendor-paid advertising</h2>
      <p>Marketing costs are paid separately from commission and typically include the cost of photography, floor plans, online listing portals (realestate.com.au and domain.com.au), print advertising if used, and any property styling or presentation work. In Brisbane's inner east, a competitive digital campaign for a family home typically costs $5,000 to $10,000 depending on the property type, the campaign duration, and the level of portal placement. Some agents bundle marketing costs into a fixed campaign fee; others present them as a separate vendor-paid advertising budget.</p>

      <p>Marketing costs are usually paid before or at the commencement of the campaign, not at settlement. Confirm the timing and method of payment with your agent when you review the marketing proposal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Total cost-to-sell: a worked example</h2>
      <p>For a Brisbane home selling at $1.2 million, the approximate costs a seller should budget are:</p>

      <div style="background:rgba(245,208,122,0.04);border:1px solid rgba(245,208,122,0.15);border-radius:4px;padding:1.25rem 1.5rem;">
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:0.9rem;">
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid rgba(245,208,122,0.1);">
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);">Agent commission at 2.2% + GST</td>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;text-align:right;color:var(--color-text-primary);">$29,040</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid rgba(245,208,122,0.1);">
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);">Marketing and vendor-paid advertising</td>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;text-align:right;color:var(--color-text-primary);">$5,000 to $10,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid rgba(245,208,122,0.1);">
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);">Legal fees and disbursements</td>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;text-align:right;color:var(--color-text-primary);">$1,500 to $3,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid rgba(245,208,122,0.1);">
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;color:var(--color-text-secondary);">Compliance certificates (pool, smoke alarm)</td>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;text-align:right;color:var(--color-text-primary);">$200 to $500</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;color:var(--color-text-primary);font-weight:600;">Total (approximate, before CGT)</td>
              <td style="padding:0.5rem 0;text-align:right;color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">$35,740 to $42,540</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>These figures are indicative for a standard Brisbane house at this price point and do not include capital gains tax, which is a separate ATO obligation for investment properties and properties that are not the seller's primary residence. CGT is calculated on the net capital gain and at the seller's marginal income tax rate, with a 50% discount available for properties held for more than 12 months. The ATO clearance certificate process is described below and is separate from CGT itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The ATO clearance certificate</h2>
      <p>For properties sold for $750,000 or more, Australian law requires the seller to provide an ATO clearance certificate at settlement, or the buyer is required to withhold 15% of the purchase price and remit it to the ATO. This is not a tax payable by the seller: it is a withholding mechanism designed to capture tax from foreign residents who sell Australian property. Australian resident sellers simply obtain the clearance certificate and provide it at settlement, which directs the buyer to pay the full purchase price rather than withholding any amount.</p>

      <p>The clearance certificate is free to apply for through the ATO's online portal. However, processing time is typically 14 to 28 days. The practical consequence for sellers is that the application should be lodged as soon as the decision to sell is made, not after the contract is signed. Lodging the application late and waiting for the certificate while a settlement date is imminent creates unnecessary pressure. Your conveyancer will remind you to obtain the certificate, but starting the process early removes a potential delay from the timeline.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Want a clear picture of your net proceeds?</strong> Before you list, Daniel will walk you through what a realistic campaign for your property would cost and what you should expect to net after all deductions. No surprises at settlement. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Get in touch.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>
</Layout>
